                        <h3 class="highlight header-colorize text-uppercase mb-4"><a href="https://www.marshall.edu/academics/programs/art-ba/">Art, B.A.</a></h3>
                            <p class="mb-4 size-18">People with creative imaginations make art to express beauty, emotion, world views or any of a multitude of concepts and ideas. Art is painting, photography, sculpture, printmaking, graphic design, digital graphics and many other ways of expression. Art attracts people who create it, write about it, teach it and take it to new levels.</p>
                              <p class="mb-4 size-18">If you are passionate about the world of Art, Marshall University, located in Huntington, West Virginia, can expand your knowledge and enhance your talents with a Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree in Art, offering two areas of emphasis: Art history and Visual Art and Design</p>
                                <p class="mb-4 size-18">The School of Art and Design at Marshall offers numerous resources to support the success of Art majors. You will be assigned to a faculty advisor/mentor who will guide you through the curriculum for a bachelor’s degree in Art and help you prepare for your future career. In addition to learning the hard skills in your Art classes, you’ll also develop other important abilities such as critical thinking and collaboration.</p>
                        <h4 class="header-colorize">Why Study Art at Marshall?</h4>
                        <p class="mb-4 size-18">The School of Art and Design provides an excellent environment to foster the appreciation, study, production and dissemination of scholarly and creative works. The Art and Design faculty, celebrated for their individual research accomplishments, are also deeply committed to teaching excellence</p>
                        <h5>Curriculum</h5>
                        <p class="mb-4 size-18">Art majors follow an interdisciplinary curriculum with both traditional and online courses that are rigorous and relevant. Class sizes are kept small so bachelor’s degree students receive in-depth instruction and plenty of personal attention.</p>
                        <p class="mb-4 size-18">The BA program at Marshall consists of two areas of emphasis: Art History and Visual Art and Design. Both BA programs require a minor outside the School of Art & Design as part of BA coursework. The purpose is for students to diversify their interests and discover parallels between their major and minor areas of study.</p>
                        <h5>Visual Art and Design</h5>
                        <p class="mb-4 size-18">This area of emphasis provides a broad studio art experience with a focus on a diverse studio art practice. Students begin their studies with Foundations Studio Art courses designed to develop a wide array of problem-solving strategies while exposing Art majors to a wide variety of art media. Students take eight studio art courses within the School of Art & Design, along with foundational Art History survey courses. The degree culminates in Capstone Studio which is designed to develop a lasting body of work and an accompanying portfolio for professional advancement. Art majors also have the option to take the Capstone exhibition for the opportunity to professionally exhibit a body of work in the Visual Arts Center’s Charles W. and Norma C. Carroll Gallery.</p>
                        <h5>Art History</h5>
                        <p class="mb-4 size-18">Majors in Art History at Marshall University gain a strong foundation in the history and theory of art. With a focus on the Western tradition, the program offers a two-semester survey of the history of art, and an array of specialized courses about the production of art, and the culture and context in which it is produced. The bachelor’s in Art degree, with an Art History track, offers an interdisciplinary approach toward understanding art and its history. Art History majors also take on a minor or second major, along with four studio art electives, in consultation with their adviser. Secondary areas in foreign language, philosophy, psychology, anthropology and sociology are encouraged.</p>
                        <p class="mb-4 size-18">Majors in Art History work in conjunction with Marshall Art History faculty through a formal Independent study to develop their Capstone research project.</p>
                        <p class="mb-4 size-18">Educational experiences. The School of Art and Design also offers annual tuition waivers and scholarships, and supports student participation in summer art residences/workshops. The faculty at the School of Art and Design understands the importance of educational experiences that extend beyond the classroom. This includes partnering with community organizations in the Huntington, WV, area, an annual trip to New York City and a summer study abroad program in Florence, Italy.</p>
