                              <h3 class="highlight header-colorize text-uppercase mb-4"><a href="https://www.marshall.edu/academics/programs/music-ba/">Music, B.A.</a></h3>
                                  <p class="mb-4 size-18">Music is created, performed and heard across all human societies. Music is played around the world, and it has existed throughout the centuries. If you love Music, your favorite genres and artists resonate with you as an essential part of life.</p>
                                    <p class="mb-4 size-18">Marshall University in Huntington, West Virginia, is deeply dedicated to the world of Music and to students who study this creative field. The School of Music’s mission is to provide enriching musical experiences for all Marshall University students; prepare Music students for pursuing careers, lifelong learning and engagement in music; and serve as an essential cultural resource for the Marshall-area region in West Virginia. The School offers 13 undergraduate and graduate programs in Music, including the Bachelor of Arts (BA) in Music.</p>
                                      <p class="mb-4 size-18">The BA in Music is a general Music degree in which majors can declare an area of emphasis (Commercial Music, Music Pedagogy, Music History, Vocal Jazz) or tailor their studies to fit their musical interests (General Emphasis). Students seeking the bachelor’s degree in Music program also must complete a minor plus additional non-music credit hours, or choose to complete a second major areas.</p>
                                      <p class="mb-4 size-18">The Bachelor of Arts in Music program at Marshall is well-suited to students who are interested in studying music at the university level, but whose interests are not a match for Marshall’s more professional Music degree programs (Performance, Music Education, etc.). This bachelor’s degree program is also a good fit for students who have more than one academic interest, as it is easy to complete a minor or a second major while earning a BA in Music degree.</p>
                              <h4 class="header-colorize">Why Study Music at Marshall?</h4>
                              <p class="mb-4 size-18">Marshall University is a fully accredited member of the National Association of Schools of Music (NASM) and has held this distinction since 1979. Recognition for Music programs at Marshall includes the recent performance of the University’s marching band in the 2020 New Year’s Day Parade in London.</p>
                              <h5>Superior Faculty</h5>
                              <p class="mb-4 size-18">The School of Music has an outstanding faculty whose members are dedicated to student success. The excellent Music faculty is international, representing seven countries on five continents. Professors are top-quality educators and caring role models, and they are successful worldwide as performers, composers and musicologists.</p>
                              <p class="mb-4 size-18">Marshall Music students perform each semester as soloists and in ensembles directed by Music faculty. Depending on individual interests, Music majors can take advantage of special research or performance projects with School of Music faculty.</p>
                              <p class="mb-4 size-18">Music majors have many performance opportunities at MU’s Smith Music Hall and Jomie Jazz Center. Marshall offers a variety of instrumental and vocal ensemble performance opportunities, and a wide range of academic programs for bachelor’s and master’s degrees in Music.</p>
                              <h5>Unique Support</h5>
                              <p class="mb-4 size-18">Marshall University’s Center for Wellness in the Arts is one of the few programs of its kind in the country. CWA provides educational, preventative and therapeutic services relating to wellness and injury prevention for performing artists studying at Marshall. Its goal is to educate Music students that pain experienced by performers is not just “part of the process,” but can and should be treated effectively. CWA includes licensed athletic trainers, skilled vocal and hearing clinicians, dietitians, exercise physiologists and performance anxiety specialists who have the proper knowledge and equipment to assess various conditions.</p>
