                                    <h3 class="highlight header-colorize text-uppercase mb-4"><a href="https://www.marshall.edu/academics/programs/theatre-ba/">Theatre, B.A.</a></h3>
                                        <p class="mb-4 size-18">The School of Theatre at Marshall University in West Virginia prepares students for a wide range of careers in the entertainment industry — whether they’re interested in performance, design or production. From stage technician to performer, there are a variety of professions where graduates can put to use all the skills they’ve developed, from creativity to collaboration to communication and problem-solving—all in a real-time environment.</p>
                                          <p class="mb-4 size-18">Located in Huntington, West Virginia, which borders both Ohio and Kentucky, Marshall offers a variety of bachelor’s degree programs in Theatre. Students may choose from among the following degree programs:</p>
                                            <p class="mb-4 size-18">The Theatre Bachelor of Arts in the Arts degree program emphasizes a breadth of content knowledge in theatre, augmented by extensive course work outside the discipline, in Music and Art. The Bachelor of Arts in the Arts program, which requires a minor, is designed to allow students maximum flexibility by pairing one of the arts with another.</p>
                                    <h4 class="header-colorize">Why Study Theatre at Marshall?</h4>
                                    <p class="mb-4 size-18">Marshall University’s Theatre major programs offer a well-rounded experience that encompasses performance and production training, while providing ample opportunity to tie in studies with other forms of the arts. Students are integrated into the performance program, regularly serving as actors, technicians and designers along with other production opportunities. Other benefits include the following:</p>
                                    <p class="mb-4 size-18">All Theatre B.A. and Theatre B.F.A. degree programs at Marshall University include mandatory advisement and professional mentoring, and an internship requirement for B.F.A. candidates, to ensure they are carefully educated and trained for their individualized goals.</p>
                                    <p class="mb-4 size-18">The programs also offer opportunities to learn outside of West Virginia and even travel abroad with financial support.</p>
                                    <p class="mb-4 size-18">The School of Theatre bachelor’s degree courses offer specialized instruction from dedicated and experienced faculty and staff, with a seven-to-one student-teacher ratio.</p>
                                    <p class="mb-4 size-18">Theatre majors study in the Joan C. Edwards Performing Arts Center, which features state-of-the-art lighting and sound systems, two fully-equipped performance spaces and a large costume and scene shop.</p>
                                    <p class="mb-4 size-18">Marshall University’s Theatre program offers students support from the Center for Wellness in the Arts, which gives them access to licensed athletic trainers, skilled vocal and hearing clinicians, dietitians, exercise physiologists and performance anxiety specialists who have the proper knowledge and equipment to assess various conditions. The center focuses on education, treatment and research to help performing arts students — who often have a mentality that a certain amount of pain is a part of the performer’s process — take care of themselves to help optimize their education and careers in the performing arts.</p>
                                    <p class="mb-4 size-18">The School of Theatre at Marshall also offers numerous scholarships and paid assistantships for students in the Theatre B.A. and Theatre B.F.A. programs.</p>
